04546nam a22005655i 9780520976870DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20232023cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209768707 a10.1525/97805209768702doi  a(DE-B1597)642452  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aSOC0260002bisacsh1 aShih, Elena, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aManufacturing Freedom :bSex Work, Anti-Trafficking Rehab, and the Racial Wages of Rescue /cElena Shih. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource (288 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction: The Slave-Free Good -- t1. The Business of Rehab: Ethical Consumption, Social Enterprise, and the Myth of Vocational Training -- t2. Manufacturing Freedom: Racialized Redemptive Labor and Sex Work -- t3. Bad Rehab: House Moms, Shelters, and Maternalist Rehabilitation -- t4. Trafficking Benevolent Authoritarianism in China -- t5. Vigilante Humanitarianism in Thailand -- t6. Quitting Rehab: The Promises and Betrayals of Freedom -- tConclusion: Redistribution and Possibilities for Global Justice -- tAcknowledgments -- tMethodological Appendix: The Embodied Currencies and Debts of Global Feminist Fieldwork -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSex worker rescue and rehabilitation programs have become a core focus of the global movement to combat human trafficking. Manufacturing Freedom offers an ethnographic exploration of two American anti-trafficking organizations that offer vocational training in jewelry production to women migrants in China and Thailand as a path out of sex work. Activists brand this jewelry a ";slave-free good"; and then sell it to consumers in the United States, generating racialized circuits of commerce and morality centered around promises of freedom from enslavement and redemptive wages for former sex workers—whom these organizations universally label as victims of trafficking. Workers, by contrast, often contest the trafficking label and object to the moral and disciplinary processes that ensnare them in a pernicious global web of anti-trafficking rescue. In this novel study, Elena Shih argues that these anti-trafficking rescue and rehabilitation projects profit off persistent labor abuse of women workers and imagined but savvily marketed narratives of redemption, thereby propagating a transnational moral economy of low-wage women's work that obfuscates relations of race, gender, national power, and inequality.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2023 Englishz978311131926108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2023z9783111318806oZDB-23-DSL08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079134140uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520976870?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520976870423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520976870/original  a978-3-11-079134-1  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  a978-3-11-131926-1  EBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2023 Englishb2023  a978-3-11-131929-2  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishb2023  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-DGGb2023  aZDB-23-DSLb2023  aZDB-23-UCY